
[1]recur

   RECUR', v.i. [L. recurro; re and curro, to run.]

   1. To return to the thought or mind.

   When any word has been used to signify an idea, the old idea will recur
   in the mind, when the word is heard.

   2. To resort; to have recourse.

   If to avoid succession in eternal existence, they recur to the punctum
   stans of the schools, they will very little help us to a more positive
   idea of infinite duration.
